text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!EndangeredLanguages]]%0a%0a!Manchu%0a%0a:Author: lauray%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aDiscussion of the Manchu Language from China%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aManchu is a language native to an area of Northeastern China that used to be known as Manchuria. It is the traditionally native language of the Manchu people, an ethnic minority in China, however most Manchu people now only speak Mandarin Chinese. It was one of the official languages of the Qing dynasty, however the usage of the language declined throughout the Qing dynasty and eventually led to it becoming endangered.%0a%0aSince there are only less than 20 native speakers worldwide, the language is considered critically endangered and is classified as between EGIDS 6b-9 on Ethnologue. It should be considered level 8b because as of 2007, the last 18 native speakers were of the grandparent generation. Several thousand people speak Manchu as a second language because of primary education and other classes in China.%0a%0aThe Manchu language started off as the primary language at the Qing Imperial court, but as time passed, these Manchu officials spoke it less and less. These officials increasingly only spoke Chinese and not Manchu to the point in which the only documents written in Manchu were memorials for the emperor. Thus, at the end of the Qing dynasty most Manchus could no longer speak their language and the Beijing dialect of Chinese replaced it because of the influence from the nation that they were in despite the incentives from the Qing government. After the Qing dynasty ended, most Manchu speakers were scared to speak it because the Han people were in charge of China again. Nowadays, Mandarin Chinese is needed to work and live in modern-day China.%0a%0aThere are revitalization efforts in place that are linked to the reconstruction of the ethnic Manchu identity in China. This began in the post-Mao era and now has support from many NGOs and other minority ethnic groups in China. These organizations offer classes at primary schools and universities, using it as a mechanism to teach reading of Qing dynasty texts. However, there are still many difficulties because China is a Han-dominated country and is still thought of as a foreign language.%0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://www.lakeforest.edu/academics/majors-and-minors/environmental-studies/the-manchu-language%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manchu_language%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210508-213522-582430#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Revitalization Efforts of the Manchu Language and What It Means  %0a-> - yuluz%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aToday, the Chinese government and some ethnic Manchurians are becoming more conscious about saving the Manchu Language. By simply googling about saving Manchu language online, we can find quite a few documentaries and news articles by the Chinese central media on the issue (links attached at the end). %0a%0aOne of the most widespread language revitalization effort is by Tan Shanshan, a cultural inheritor of the Manchu language. He opened both online and offline classes in China to help save the language. The hashtag for his online classes earned 160 million views on China's social media Weibo, with many Chinese netizens saying they support the conservation of China's ethnic minority languages. %0a%0aHowever, given the prevalence of Mandarin in China today, I think it is nearly impossible for people to begin use the Manchu language in daily interactions again even after they have learned it. I agree with many scholars that the importance of preserving this language lies more in its research value. Since the Manchu language was one of the official languages of the Manchu-led Qing Dynasty(1644-1911), many scripts and documents from that time period were written in this language. Thus, preserving the language is critical for the study of that 300 years of history in China. %0a%0aReports on revitalization efforts of the Manchu Language:%0a1. Plans to save ‘critically endangered’ Manchu language are spreading to preserve ethnic culture (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X1eeAGr-jzs)%0a2. Saving the Manchu Language (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nCFG-cbQOJc)%0a3. Cultural inheritor opens classes to save endangered Manchu language (https://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1172117.shtml)%0a%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-213522-582430#%0a#foxbegin 210509-032632-469470#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!A small glimpse into Manchu morphology %0a-> - ruiranx%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aUnlike Mandarin Chinese, Manchu is an agglutinative language, and grammatical characteristics of all parts of speech are encoded through suffixation or infixation. As an example, we'll take a look at nouns, which can occur in five cases: nominative, genitive, accusative, dative, and ablative. [1]%0a%0a1. Nominative nouns are used as the subject of a sentence. They are unmarked, so the bare stem of a noun is also the nominative noun.%0a2. Genitive nouns are used to modify other words. They are marked by appending "i", unless the bare stem ends with "ng", in which case "ni" is added separately from the noun (e.g. niyalma -> niyalmai, tsang -> tsang ni).%0a3. Accusative nouns are typically direct objects. They are denoted by adding "be" separately (e.g. buda -> buda be).%0a4. Dative nouns are typically indirect objects. They're formed by adding "de", either through suffixation (unless the terminal consonant of the bare stem is not "n") or written separately (e.g. orin -> orin de, boo -> boode). %0a5. Ablative nouns typically play an agentive role. They are marked by suffixation or separate addition of "ci", following the same exception as the dative case (e.g. alin -> alin ci, ere -> ereci).%0a%0a[1] https://www.manchustudiesgroup.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Lesson-6-Noun-Cases.pdf%0a%0aSide note: some real serious agglutination action can be seen in Manchu verb derivatives, as seen in [2].%0a%0a[2] https://www.manchustudiesgroup.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Lesson-14-Verbs-IV-derivational-suffixes.pdf%0a%0aAlso honestly, this entire website [3] is worth perusing; I think I'll try to take some time over the summer to look this over!%0a%0a[3] https://www.manchustudiesgroup.org/introduction-to-manchu-in-21-lessons/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-032632-469470#%0a#foxbegin 210514-050503-73310#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!More about Manchu Language %0a-> - saumyaB%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aBelow is a link to a video by Manchu speakers discussing the Manchu language in China. It was very cool to hear the similarities and differences to Mandarin when the Manchu speakers were speaking Manchu. According to this video, there was a nationwide policy to preserve several languages in 2005 including Manchu. In Fuyu county in China, this policy resulted in the establishment of a Manchu school, where young students learn the Manchu language and culture. However, many parents are less interested in sending their kids to these schools as Mandarin is now the main language, and a lot of them don’t see any benefits to learning the dying language, as it isn’t used outside these villages. Even the elder speakers of the language comment on it dying, mentioning that they themselves may not remember certain phrases of the language.%0a%0aI also scrolled down to the comment section, and it appears that a few people around the world in different countries have tried to pick up Manchu.%0a%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pHr1f5V2hzA&ab_channel=SixthTone%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210514-050503-73310#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: D:)%0a(:Category: EndangeredLanguages:)
